This solidarity group is called "Los Cedros,'  and is made up of these members: 

Justina is going to use her loan to buy notebooks, pencils, paints, modelling clay, glue and binders; 

Ever is going to buy lingerie, blouses, and dress pants; 

Mario is going to buy a licence for his taxi; 

Elizabeth is going to buy organic and chemical fertilizer; 

Rosalinda is going to buy thread, fabric, paints, and needles. Rosalinda is 43 years old. She is married, and her husband is a taxi driver. She has eight children: six girls and one boy. Only three girls are in school; two are in junior high school and one in primary, and one boy is in high school. 

She sells embroidered and painted serving cloths. She applied for her loan to buy thread, fabric, paints, and needles in order to have materials for embroidering and painting the serving cloths. A part of the loan is for food. 

She began her business 25 years ago with a fabric remnant that she was given. She cut it, embroidered it, and sold it. With that she started buying her material. Now she has her orders for work she does at home.

Her business is important because it provides financial support that benefits her family. Her hopes and dreams are to have a shop where she can sell her products and for her children to have a better future. 

The members of the group want to say to Kiva and Fundación Realidad: “Thank you very much for lending to us, we wish you many blessings, and hope you continue supporting us with your loans so that the businesses grow."
